\fs36 \cf2 About the Styles Used
\fs24 \cf0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\sl360\slmult1\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}This template contains the most common styles used for comics: 
\i Page Number, Panel Number, Panel Description, Character, Dialogue
\i0  and 
\i Parenthetical
\i0 .\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\sl360\slmult1\pardirnatural\qj\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\b \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}Page Number
\b0  appears only once for each page, at the top of the document. Pressing TAB after typing will insert the <$N> character string, which will be replaced with sequential numbering upon compile and so allows you to auto-number your pages.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\b {\listtext	\'95	}Panel Number
\b0  is used to denote a single panel of comic art on the page. Press TAB after typing to insert the <$sn> string, which will auto-number your panels within each page during the Compile process. Press ENTER to automatically put the text into 
\i Panel Description
\i0  mode.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\b {\listtext	\'95	}Panel Description
\b0  is used to describe the image within each panel of art. Multiple paragraphs of 
\i Panel Description
\i0  text can be used in a panel description. Therefore, press ENTER after typing to keep the text in 
\i Panel Description
\i0  mode. To enter 
\i Character
\i0  mode, press TAB either after typing, or while on a blank line.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\b {\listtext	\'95	}Character
\b0  denotes a speaking character within a panel, and precedes their dialogue. Press ENTER to put the text into 
\i Dialogue
\i0  mode. Press TAB to make notes on lettering style for the dialogue that follows, e.g. \'93Large\'94, \'93Small\'94, \'93Jagged\'94, or \'93Off\'94 (useful for when a speaking character is not visible in panel). These notes are usually made in parentheses, so in this template a left parenthesis (i.e. the \'93
\b (
\b0 \'94 character) is automatically inserted after the character\'92s name, and the auto-complete library for this style contains text with closed parentheses. \
{\listtext	\'95	}Caption boxes are regarded as dialogue, and so \'93CAPTION\'94 should be used in place of a character name, followed by the text to appear in the box.\
{\listtext	\'95	}Sound effects are similarly denoted with \'93SFX\'94.\
{\listtext	\'95	}If a panel is completely silent (i.e. has no dialogue, caption or sound effect) then a character of \'93NO DIALOGUE\'94 should be entered, ending the panel.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\b {\listtext	\'95	}Dialogue
\b0  is the speech of each character. Dialogue is not broken up into true paragraphs. Therefore, press ENTER to move the text back into 
\i Panel Description
\i0  mode. If you wish to break a long section of dialogue into multiple balloons, press TAB to enter 
\i Parenthetical
\i0  mode.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\b {\listtext	\'95	}Parenthetical
\b0  is used to link together multiple dialogue balloons spoken by the same character in a single panel. Simply type \'93cont\'94 and hit either TAB or ENTER; parentheses will automatically be placed around the \'93cont\'94 text, and the text will return to 
\i Dialogue
\i0  mode on a new line.\
{\listtext	\'95	}Other lettering notes can also be made in the parentheticals after the \'93cont\'94 text, e.g. \'93cont, small\'94 or \'93cont, jagged\'94. Lettering notes that affect the entire dialogue should be made on the 
\i Character
\i0  line, as noted above.\
